Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["4) ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "Now use the function GroupBy to group the data by gender and calculate the \
mean for the gender"
}], "Subchapter",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.778957215235772*^9, 3.77895723261709*^9}, {
  3.778957267469329*^9, 3.7789572798855877`*^9}},
 FontSize->12,ExpressionUUID->"5883ddee-8320-4b89-b735-021e669e8b3d"],

Cell["\<\
Notice bellow the difference between GroubBy (creates a list of two lists \
each with several elements) and GatherBy (creates a list of 8 elements) :\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7742565923956547`*^9, 3.7742566026175823`*^9}, {
  3.774599680365679*^9, 3.7745997048547363`*^9}},
 FontSize->12,ExpressionUUID->"156dd518-0235-4ef6-bb3b-b3e37a579b1a"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
MapReduce operations (standard in NoSQL queries...) on Dataset objects\
\>", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.710756382837063*^9, 3.7107563957391644`*^9}, {
  3.7789359423553257`*^9, 3.77893595024218*^9}},
 FontSize->12,ExpressionUUID->"03b60c32-a963-4d6e-aca8-4c09699e53b2"],

Cell["\<\
Now, calculate the mean ages of the genders, grouping the data and then \
performing aggregation operation on the groups. This types of operations are \
sometimes known as a MapReduce. It\[CloseCurlyQuote]s also sometimes known as \
a rollup or an aggregation.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.710271761273983*^9, 3.710271798240875*^9}, {
  3.710756400892321*^9, 3.710756435517398*^9}, {3.7122423634016514`*^9, 
  3.712242372377199*^9}, {3.7789575094865417`*^9, 3.778957580195291*^9}},
 FontSize->12,ExpressionUUID->"4ae146a7-5bce-42d8-accc-2548e0dd6c58"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["5) ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "Now, with a single command, group by gender and calculate the mean"
}], "Subchapter",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.778957527841647*^9, 3.778957530370693*^9}, {
   3.778957594825995*^9, 3.778957620292235*^9}, {3.778957741747713*^9, 
   3.778957743921296*^9}, 3.77895829291833*^9},
 FontSize->12,ExpressionUUID->"84190a5c-f45c-469f-8130-917920e57c2e"],

Cell["", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7102720867133923`*^9, 3.710272102672038*^9}, {
   3.7102736555571747`*^9, 3.710273661109342*^9}, 3.7789576984237623`*^9},
 FontSize->12,ExpressionUUID->"daa6914e-5339-4236-9201-19d726848439"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["6)",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " Create a function to creates a query that can run any operation (not just \
computing the mean) on the Dataset grouped by gender and then working on \
age."
}], "Subchapter",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7107568147024527`*^9, 3.7107568533586583`*^9}, {
  3.7107568900582104`*^9, 3.7107568930108256`*^9}, {3.7789577242529287`*^9, 
  3.7789577589973183`*^9}},
 FontSize->12,ExpressionUUID->"e0a281cf-5329-4047-aecd-637f28f15fc2"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["", "SlideShowNavigationBar",
 CellTags->
  "SlideShowHeader",ExpressionUUID->"4adc4df2-ddab-4dfc-bbd1-500669cfe166"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
7) Constructions of Association, and datasets from lists. Use the List t.\
\>", "Subchapter",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7102721061903667`*^9, 3.7102721122969007`*^9}, {
  3.778957815341297*^9, 3.778957825701023*^9}, {3.778958215201627*^9, 
  3.778958218858787*^9}, {3.778958253578445*^9, 3.7789582541333113`*^9}},
 FontSize->12,ExpressionUUID->"2f906040-de9d-4226-bf8c-f24fa3bc2505"],

Cell["\<\
Very often, a dataset has a unique row of keys, and them several rows of \
values. This type of data needs to be pre-processed to be treated as an \
Association or a Dataset. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.77895794706544*^9, 3.778958021515375*^9}},
 FontSize->12,ExpressionUUID->"df6e7fc0-0a1c-47c5-8bd3-f9595eb23630"],

Cell["The function to be used is the AssociationThread", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.778958034341731*^9, 3.778958050415159*^9}, {
  3.778958084526346*^9, 3.778958086228012*^9}},
 FontSize->12,ExpressionUUID->"001d3399-937c-4f2b-abc8-44a0f20feed3"],

Cell["\<\
 The first argument in this function is the list of things that go on the \
left hand side of the Rules -- the \"keys\" -- and the second argument is the \
list of things that go on the right hand side of the Rules -- the \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]values\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote].\
\>", "Text",
